Observation Details: Large nuthatch with blue-gray upper back & dark wings. Black or dark head above eyes extending from base of beak to crown/nape and down to back of head/neck. All white face with barely detectable line or darker area behind eye. Chin, breast & belly all white, no streaking or pale other coloration. Did not see under tail or vent color but appeared light. Tail feathers & primaries appeared black or dark & edged in white. The birds did not vocalize.  Two separate birds were seen by both observers. The one we both observed appeared to be a male since it was very dark or black on crown & wing areas. Were found in a riparian habitat with perennial running creek & many mature deciduous trees. Were seen foraging on trunks of large Willow & Cottonwood trees about 10+ ft. above on or near other large limbs. These birds were also seen on 27 Apr. 2020 in approximately the same location by another group of 4 observers & reported to eBird.

Observation Details: Was seen in riparian area on low bush above grasses next to a perennial creek surrounded by deciduous trees. Sparrow was seen carrying a bug while sitting on a twig, then flying off. Observed face pattern & light body streaking. Showed eye ring & also brown shoulder patch when it stretched wings to fly off. Typical size & behavior for Vesper's Sparrow in grass. Cienega Creek is in a riparian area surrounded by grassland & desert areas near foothills. Rechecked ID & typical species habitation after arriving back home. Have seen this species near water & grasses in other Pima County areas.

Observation Details: This highly deciduously forested Natural Riparian Area with running creek tulles & undergrowth has been annually visited & resided in thru the Spring/Summer months by this species. It is not uncommon to hear several different calling Chats within this 2-mi. transect area where avian activity & breeding is at its peak. Many Chats were seen but more were heard. Their calls are diagnostic & their dangling feet, awkward flights were observed as well. Past annual counts here have shown the numbers of Chats recorded as a common occurrence.

Please note that this particular count in this section (Cienega Creek, Pima County) was particularly high in species numbers & numbers of individuals from several years past. This year's Spring migration appears to be pulling in more migrants than have previously been reported in TBC history. I suspect more species & numbers will arrive soon.
